image.alt_text: Photo by 𝔸𝕤𝕤𝕠𝕔𝕚𝕒𝕥𝕚𝕠𝕟 𝕁𝕚𝕓𝕠𝕚𝕒𝕟𝕒 in Forêt Amazonienne with @leo.landon.jiboiana, @celia.xakriaba, and @association_jiboiana. May be an image of one or more people and outdoors.
image.caption:
Partout sur la planète, après des siècles de mise sous silence, les femmes autochtones se lèvent, et luttent pour leurs droits, leurs terres, et la préservation de tous les êtres vivants ✊🏽🌎🪶🌿

Dans un mouvement magique et synchronisé, notre monde voit émerger les voix complémentaires des femmes, des peuples autochtones et de la Nature. Si le féminisme, la reconnaissance du rôle de ces peuples et l’écologie avancent main dans la main dans de plus en plus de cœurs, il ne s’agit pas d’un hasard - mais d’un attendu rendez-vous.

Chaque fois que l’humanité asservissait plus les uns, elle asservissait simultanément plus les autres. Car les femmes sont partie intégrante de l’origine du monde, là d’où chaque être est né ; et les peuples autochtones, connectés à la Terre, font encore un avec elle - alors que nos sociétés nous ont éminemment coupés de nos racines.

C’est pourquoi des hommes ont érigé des principes de séparation pour pouvoir dominer et exploiter : les hommes sont supérieurs aux femmes qui doivent être au service ; les peuples autochtones sont des sous-hommes, et doivent donc être au service ; et nous sommes au-dessus de la Nature, donc elle doit être au service.

Mais aujourd’hui, nous sommes heureux de constater que ces paradigmes désolants, qui ont régné pendant d’innombrables années, sont des colosses aux pieds d’argile : car des hommes soutiennent les femmes qui s’émancipent, des Occidentaux soutiennent des peuples autochtones, et de plus en plus d’âmes veulent stopper cette folie de destruction de la Nature. Dans tout ce chaos, l’espoir renaît et des lumières fleurissent.

Merci à vous toutes et tous qui soutenez Jiboiana - ensemble, union des colibris, nous réalisons ce que l’on pensait impossible !

image.alt_text: Photo by 𝔸𝕤𝕤𝕠𝕔𝕚𝕒𝕥𝕚𝕠𝕟 𝕁𝕚𝕓𝕠𝕚𝕒𝕟𝕒 in Brazil with @leo.landon.jiboiana, @yarikazu_xipaya, and @association_jiboiana. May be an image of 1 person and outdoors.
image.caption:
Parole de l’activiste Yarikazu, du peuple autochtone Xipaya en Amazonie 🪶✊🏽 : 

« 521 ans ont passé depuis le début de notre combat. L’invasion de nos territoires a déclenché un génocide sans précédent contre les peuples autochtones, et qui persiste encore aujourd’hui. Mais, en plus de cet affront, ils nous ont fait croire que c’étaient nous les envahisseurs, et que nous ne devrions pas être ici.

Mais la force qui nous guide est ancestrale, naturelle et divine. C’est ce lien incassable avec la forêt, et il est certain que le Brésil est une terre autochtone car dans chacune de ses parties le sang de mes ancêtres a été versé, le même qui coule aujourd’hui dans mes veines.

Socialement, le simple fait d’être une femme, est déjà discriminant dans ce monde patriarchal - et souvent nous sommes sous-estimées ou même carrément oubliées. Naître femme et naître autochtone, c’est déjà en soi résister.
Alors amies et amis, autochtones ou non, joignons nos âmes et nos forces pour poursuivre ensemble cette lutte planétaire ! »
@yarikazu_xipaya 

Merci aux jeunes activistes et leaders spirituels des peuples autochtones, gardiens de la Nature, pour leur lutte et leurs messages de paix et de préservation !

This Valentine's Day, we partnered with @FutureKokum to create a product to honour MMIWG2S victims and their families. aaniin is donating 100% of the profits to The Native Women's Resource Centre of Toronto www.NWRCT.ca.

The misko tuque features hand-beaded vegan leather patches by @futurekokum. The syllabics write gaawiin geyaabi, which means "no more". 

Statistics show that Indigenous women, girls and two spirits are at considerable risk of being victims of violence. We will never see the true statistics and we wear misko to honour them and as a call to action for no more violence to occur. 

IWG2S deserve love, respect, and community, they deserve to be seen, heard, and accounted for. 

Use the hashtags #whywewearred #MMIWG2S #Nomorestolensisters  #gaawiingeyaabi #notinvisible to show your support for the victims and their families. 

chi miigwech for your support and donations you can always donate directly on the NWRCT.ca website.

image.caption:
Action shot of Warlpiri artist, Pauline Napangardi Gallagher putting the finishing touches on her latest painting! 💗 

Born in the remote region of Yuendumu in 1952, Pauline began working with the Warlukurlangu Artists in 2006 and loves to paint her Father’s stories – Pikilyi Jukurrpa (Pikilyi Dreaming) and Mina Mina Jukurrpa (Mina Mina Dreaming) as well as Dreamings related to her land & it's animals. These stories have been passed down to her by her parents and their parents before them for millennia.

I am honored and thrilled to welcome Crystal to @TheLisaEkusGroup!

Crystal Wahpepah is an enrolled member of the Kickapoo nation of Oklahoma Sack and Fox Nation. She was born and raised in Oakland, Ca. Through Wahpepah’s Kitchen, Crystal aims to acknowledge that we live on stolen land and talk about how that acknowledgement connects to the reclamation of Native food ways, as well as to educate communities and organizations on the health benefits of Native food ways using the knowledge passed onto her from her family.

Crystal received the Indigenous Artist Activist Award and has been inducted into the Native American Almanac for being one of the first Native American women to own a catering business in Oakland, Ca. In 2016, she was the first Native American Chef to compete in the Food Network’s show, Chopped.
Welcome to the agency, Crystal! Head over to the agency page for more info!

image.caption:
She was molded by the prayers of her ancestors, she was protected by the mountains that called her name. She was born into a realm that wasn't ready for the truth of what truly happened to her people. She craved to see her Secwepemc relatives living life in the mountains by the water as they were created to do so. Ceremony and prayers stimulated all that was buried underneath the concrete we walked on. She was the Matriarch that was breaking down the patriarchal walls. She dreams  of the day she witnesses Secwepemc woman on the land,  the day she revitalizes  a women's lodge/pithome for her sisters to spirituality gather without violence. To make sure her sisters make it to the land  before they are missing. Her dreams were much bigger then her, so collective healing is what will be the revolution. In her blood she was Tsi7kwa from a time before this one.

Special Report From the Intelligence Cell: Ep #64 Murdered and Missing in Montana with Loni Coombs. @laurarichards999 interviews former LA prosecutor and legal expert @lonicoombs about her new @oxygen documentary Murdered and Missing Montana. Gabby Petito’s case received a lot of media attention – and started a conversation about the fact that Native American women and girls are the most stalked, raped and murdered in America yet no-one is talking about them. 

Indigenous women are 10 times more likely to be killed than the national average. And Indigenous girls and women aged between 10-34 years of age the third most prevalent cause of death is murder. 94% of Native America women will be raped or coerced in their lifetime. We get into how and why and we discuss three cases in particular, Selena Not Afraid, Kaysera Stops Pretty Places and Henny Scott.

.
